## 🔑 Key Embryological Origins
- Gonads (both sexes) develop from **urogenital ridge** (intermediate mesoderm)
- **Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts** → uterus, uterine tubes, upper vagina (female)
- **Wolffian (mesonephric) ducts** → epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicles (male)
- External genitalia are indifferent until week 9; DHT drives male differentiation

## 🏥 Clinical Significance

| Condition | Structure Involved | Key Point |
|-----------|-------------------|-----------|
| Testicular torsion | [[Spermatic Cord]] | Surgical emergency; bell-clapper deformity |
| Varicocele | Pampiniform plexus (left > right) | Dilated venous plexus; cause of male infertility |
| Benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) | [[Prostate Gland]] | Median lobe → urinary outflow obstruction |
| Prostate cancer | [[Prostate Gland]] | Posterior zone; screened with PSA |
| Ectopic pregnancy | [[Uterine Tubes]] | Ampullary region most common; surgical emergency |
| Ovarian torsion | [[Ovaries]] | Sudden pelvic pain; requires urgent surgery |
| Cervical cancer | [[Cervix]] | HPV 16/18; screened with Pap smear |
| Uterine fibroids | [[Uterus]] | Leiomyoma; most common benign uterine tumour |
| Endometriosis | [[Uterus]], ovaries, peritoneum | Ectopic endometrial tissue; cyclical pain |

